            en: "<b>POSTFACE</b><br>(1 John 4/12) <b>â€œNo one has ever seen God; if we love one another, God lives in us, and His love is made complete in us.â€</b><br><br>(Exodus 33/20) <b>â€œThe Lord said: You cannot see My face, for no one may see Me and live.â€</b> (See page 80)<br><br>The four Gospels report these words of Jesus: (Matthew 5/9) <b>â€œBlessed are those who spread peace around them, for God will recognize them as His sons.â€</b><br><br>The word <b>â€œsonâ€</b> cannot be taken literally. Indeed, in the Bible, God refers to several of His servants as <b>â€œsonsâ€</b>. The Hebrews believe that God is One and has neither wife nor children in the literal sense. It is therefore clear that the expression <b>â€œson of Godâ€</b> actually means <b>â€œservant of Godâ€</b> and refers to a pious person close to God, as a son is close to his father.<br><br>(Hebrews 1/5) <b>â€œFor to which of the angels did God ever say: You are My Son, today I have begotten You? Or again: I will be His Father, and He will be My Son?â€</b><br><br>Christians of Greek or Roman culture later misused this expression. Thus, <b>â€œson of Godâ€</b> became a divine incarnation or referred to a person born from the physical union of male and female deities. In (Acts 14/11-13), it is recounted that when Paul and Barnabas went to preach in a city in Turkey, the pagans claimed they were incarnated gods. They called Barnabas Jupiter and Paul Mercury.<br><br>Elsewhere, the Greek terms translated as <b>â€œsonâ€</b> in the New Testament are *pios* and *paidos* (Ï€Î±á¿–Ï‚). These mean <b>â€œservantâ€</b> or <b>â€œson in the sense of servantâ€</b>. These terms are translated as <b>â€œsonâ€</b> for Jesus and <b>â€œservantâ€</b> for others in most Bible translations. But if we are honest, it is clear that Jesus was only saying he was truly the servant of God.<br><br>(Qurâ€™an 3/59) <b>â€œIndeed, the example of Jesus to Allah is like that of Adam, whom He created from dust, then said to him, â€˜Be,â€™ and he was.â€</b><br><br>(Qurâ€™an 112/3) <b>â€œAllah has not begotten (He has no son and is not the father of anyone), nor was He begotten (He has no father or mother).â€</b><br><br>This is why God does not use the word â€œFatherâ€ in the Qurâ€™an, as people might misinterpret or misunderstand it. Instead, He used the word *Ar-Rabb*, which means: the Creator, the King, the Sovereignâ€¦ Thus, in truth, the term â€œson of Godâ€ means His messenger or a pious person.<br><br>Often, followers of Christianity view Jesus as a prophet, others as the son of God, others as a God incarnate, others as one of the three persons of the Trinity, and others, rejecting the Trinity, see Him as the sole supreme being to worship; the Creator. Let us ask ourselves a question:<br>",
