            en: "<b>**The Question of Sin**</b><br>The Quran is clear on this point: humans are frail and often fall into sin, for we are not angels! The Muslim is called to live a life of repentance and to hope for Godâ€™s mercy:<br><br>(Quran 39/53, Sahih International) <b>'Say, Â«O My servants who have transgressed against themselves [by sinning], do not despair of the mercy of Allah. Indeed, Allah forgives all sins. Indeed, it is He who is the Forgiving, the Merciful.Â»'</b><br><br>Christians, on the other hand, believe that Jesus died on the cross for the sins of humanity: whoever believes in Jesus is forgiven and saved, but whoever does not believe will die with their sins and be eternally condemned. Yet, is Allahâ€™s mercy not sufficient for the forgiveness of sins? Before Jesusâ€™ coming, in the Old Testament, forgiveness of sins was already granted through sincere repentance.<br><br>Christians, in their prayers, sing and thank Jesus, believing he forgave their sins in advance through his death. However, Jesus had already spoken about such an attitude. Indeed, in the parable of the Pharisee and the tax collector (Luke 18:9-15, NIV), it is written: <b>'Two men went up to the temple to pray.'</b><br><br>Doesnâ€™t the Pharisee resemble some Christians when he says: <b>'God, I thank you that I am not like other peopleâ€”robbers, evildoers, adulterersâ€”or even like this tax collector. I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get.'</b><br><br>Like these Christians, this Pharisee believed himself justified, holy, and saved. Compare him to the tax collector, who <b>'stood at a distance. He would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, Â«God, have mercy on me, a sinner.Â»'</b> Doesnâ€™t this tax collector resemble a Muslim, who acknowledges their faults and sins, humbles themselves before Allah, and pleads for His forgiveness?<br><br>Jesus continues: <b>'I tell you that this man, rather than the other, went home justified before God. For all those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted.'</b><br><br>Furthermore, it is unthinkable and illogical for one personâ€™s sin to be borne by another. It is obvious that each person must take responsibility for their own actions. Indeed, the Bible confirms this: <b>'The one who sins is enrolment who pays the price. The son will not bear the fatherâ€™s guilt, nor will the father bear the sonâ€™s. The righteousness of the righteous person will be credited to their own account, and the wickedness of the wicked will be charged against them.'â€™(Ezekiel 18:20, NIV)</b><br>In the Christian tradition, it is believed that the original sin, committed by Adam and Eve, is passed down to all humanity.<br><br>This concept is closely linked to the teachings of Paul, particularly in his letters to the Romans. A key verse on this is: <b>Â«Therefore, just as sin entered the world through one man, and death through sin, and in this way death came to all people, because all sinned.Â»</b>(Romans 5:12, NIV)<br><br>According to this belief, all humans are born sinners due to the disobedience of the first humans. For example, even a child at birth is considered to carry this original sin.. However, from an Islamic perspective, while Adamâ€™s sin is a significant event in history, it is not passed down to future generations..<br><br>Indeed, God forgave Adam after his sincere repentance, as indicated in the Quran (20/121-122, Sahih International): <b>'And Adam disobeyed his Lord and erred. Then his Lord chose him and turned to him in forgiveness and guided him.'</b><br><br>Thus, Adamâ€™s sin does not directly affect us, and each individual is responsible for their own deeds.",
